<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25175a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25175a">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25175a"> 175(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">H</font> couvade</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It has been supposed that the Iberians, who mingled with the Kelts in Spain, were of this non-Aryan race which never reached Britain. The Basques have retained the strange custom of the <mark><i>couvade</i></mark>, or &ldquo;hatch-/ing,&rdquo; which obliges the father to nurse the baby in bed for some days after its birth. Diodorus mentions this custom in Corsica, and Strabo among the Tibareni of Asia Minor. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 52-3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Sympathetic pregnancy is referred to as <i>couvade</i> syndrome: a condition in which the male experiences many of the same symptoms and behaviors of an expectant mother.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14118h" href="c14all.htm#c14118h">VI.C.14:118(h)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
